+{-| Start a named timer in the developer console, and then return the value
+unchanged.
+
+```
+expensiveValue
+  |> time "calculation"
+  |> calculate
+  |> timeEnd "calculation"
+```
+
+This makes it possible to insert timing measurements into pipelines without
+changing the resulting value. The timer continues running until a matching
+[`timeEnd`](#timeEnd) call uses the same label.
+
+You can use [`timeLog`](#timeLog) to print intermediate measurements without
+stopping the timer.
+
+```
+value
+  |> time "render"
+  |> prepare
+  |> timeLog "render"
+  |> draw
+  |> timeEnd "render"
+```
+
+Timer labels should be unique while a timer is running. Starting another timer
+with the same label may produce a warning in the developer console.
+
+**Note:** This is intended for development and debugging. It is not available
+with `elm make --optimize` because it performs an observable side effect whose
+behavior could become unpredictable when compiler optimizations move or remove
+code.
+-}
+time : String -> value -> value
+time =
+  Elm.Kernel.Debug.time
+
+{-| Log the current duration of a named timer in the developer console, and
+then return the value unchanged.
+
+The timer must first be started with [`time`](#time) using the same label.
+
+```
+value
+  |> time "loading"
+  |> loadMetadata
+  |> timeLog "loading"
+  |> loadContent
+  |> timeEnd "loading"
+```
+
+Calling `timeLog` does not stop or reset the timer, so it can be used multiple
+times to inspect intermediate timings.
+
+```
+value
+  |> time "process"
+  |> firstStep
+  |> timeLog "process" "message after first step"
+  |> secondStep
+  |> timeLog "process" "message after second step"
+  |> finalStep
+  |> timeEnd "process"
+```
+
+The current Elm value may also be displayed alongside the elapsed time,
+depending on the runtime implementation.
+
+**Note:** This is intended for development and debugging. It is not available
+with `elm make --optimize` because it performs an observable side effect whose
+behavior could become unpredictable when compiler optimizations move or remove
+code.
+-}
+timeLog : String -> String -> value -> value
+timeLog =
+  Elm.Kernel.Debug.timeLog
+
+{-| Stop a named timer, log its total duration in the developer console, and
+then return the value unchanged.
+
+The timer must first be started with [`time`](#time) using the same label.
+
+```
+result =
+  input
+    |> time "parse"
+    |> parse
+    |> timeEnd "parse"
+```
+
+After `timeEnd` is called, the timer with that label is removed and the same
+label can be used to start a new measurement.
+
+```
+firstResult =
+  firstInput
+    |> time "operation"
+    |> calculate
+    |> timeEnd "operation"
+
+secondResult =
+  secondInput
+    |> time "operation"
+    |> calculate
+    |> timeEnd "operation"
+```
+
+Calling `timeEnd` without a matching timer may produce a warning in the
+developer console.
+
+**Note:** This is intended for development and debugging. It is not available
+with `elm make --optimize` because it performs an observable side effect whose
+behavior could become unpredictable when compiler optimizations move or remove
+code.
+-}
+timeEnd : String -> value -> value
+timeEnd =
+  Elm.Kernel.Debug.timeEnd
+
+{-| Start a named CPU profile in the developer tools, and then return the value
+unchanged.
+
+```
+value
+  |> profile "expensive calculation"
+  |> calculate
+  |> profileEnd "expensive calculation"
+```
+
+Unlike [`time`](#time), which only measures the total elapsed duration, a CPU
+profile can show which JavaScript functions used the most processing time
+during the recorded section.
+
+The resulting profile is normally available in the performance or profiler
+panel of the developer tools. Exact behavior and availability depend on the
+browser or JavaScript runtime.
+
+Profiles should always be paired with a matching [`profileEnd`](#profileEnd)
+call using the same label.
+
+**Note:** Profiling is not supported by every developer console. On unsupported
+platforms, this function may have no visible effect.
+
+**Note:** This is intended for development and debugging. It is not available
+with `elm make --optimize` because it performs an observable side effect whose
+behavior could become unpredictable when compiler optimizations move or remove
+code.
+-}
+profile : String -> value -> value
+profile =
+  Elm.Kernel.Debug.profile
+
+{-| Stop a named CPU profile in the developer tools, and then return the value
+unchanged.
+
+The profile must first be started with [`profile`](#profile) using the same
+label.
+
+```
+decoded =
+  bytes
+    |> profile "decode"
+    |> decode
+    |> profileEnd "decode"
+```
+
+After the profile is stopped, the developer tools can display information such
+as function call counts, call stacks, and the amount of CPU time spent in
+different parts of the generated JavaScript.
+
+Exact results and presentation depend on the browser or JavaScript runtime.
+
+**Note:** Profiling is not supported by every developer console. On unsupported
+platforms, this function may have no visible effect.
+
+**Note:** This is intended for development and debugging. It is not available
+with `elm make --optimize` because it performs an observable side effect whose
+behavior could become unpredictable when compiler optimizations move or remove
+code.
+-}
+profileEnd : String -> value -> value
+profileEnd =
+  Elm.Kernel.Debug.profileEnd
